> For the lock, let's take Dictionary as an example, we can use normal Dictionary in our code, apply lock whenever we need to access it. Or we can use ConcurrentDictionay that itself is thread safe, the caller doesn't need to worry about the lock. 

This is not true. Using only thread safe classes does not make a class thread safe. Consider the following case:

``` C#
namespace ThreadSafety
{
    internal class Problematic
    {
        private readonly ConcurrentDictionary<int, int> _dictionary = new ConcurrentDictionary<int, int>();

        internal void Increment(int key)
        {
            _dictionary[key] = Get(key) + 1;
        }

        internal int Get(int key)
        {
            if (_dictionary.ContainsKey(key))
            {
                return _dictionary[key];
            }
            return 0;
        }

        public void WreckHavoc()
        {
            var random = new Random();
            const int maxIndex = 100;

            while (true)
            {
                {
                    var index = (int)(random.NextDouble() * maxIndex);
                    var oldValue = Get(index);
                    Increment(index);
                    var newValue = Get(index);
                    if (newValue != oldValue + 1)
                    {
                        throw new Exception("Synchronization error.");
                    }
                }
            }
        }

    }


    internal class Program
    {
        private static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            var problematicInstance = new Problematic();

            const int nThreads = 12;
            var threads = new Thread[nThreads];

            for (var i = 0; i < nThreads; ++i)
            {
                threads[i] = new Thread(problematicInstance.WreckHavoc);
                threads[i].Start();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Clearly, we are only using thread safe attribute types. Yet, the class as a whole isn't thread safe.

We need the Driver to be thread safe here. For that, it doesn't matter whether the state machine classes are thread safe. The code above would be equally wrong if it used mere `Dictionary` instances.

@tcNickolas both `Exception`s are out of the scope of this PR, but answering your questions
1. Yes. This is by design, same goes in the Java side. This is because if an Task receives a `CloseEvent` when it shouldn't, it should not be ignored. In this case, when the Evaluator is force-shut-down, a `CloseEvent` is sent to the Task to try to warn it such that a user may have a chance to perform some sort of state-preserving operation. If the user does not choose to implement the Handler for `CloseEvent`, the Task will be force-shut-down anyhow.
2. This is relevant to the work to be done in [REEF-1286](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/REEF-1286). If the Evaluator fails on a .NET failure, Java cannot deserialize it.

@markusweimer See Jon Skeet's comment here:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1888310/c-sharp-sharing-locks-with-multithreading
It's definitely not ideal, but it's explicit as to what to lock on. An alternative is to do as you say as done in Java, but that should not be in conflict with the principle of not locking on `this` within the class itself.
